      "role": "user",
      "content": "\"dangerous oversimplification\" is a pretty strong way to put it. i just don't see why the \"work disincentive\" has to be treated as the \"core\" principle when things like rising cost of living or childcare costs also drive labor decisions. if a policy actually helps people stay stable enough to eventually find better jobs, isn't that also an economic benefit? it feels like you're framing the debate as if the choice is only between work and being lazy.",
